The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Ambala, Feb. 25: Hallmarking of gold jewellery will be mandatory from January next year, the Bureau of Indian Standards (BIS) said today. The move, which has the Centres approval, will cover over 3 lakh jewellery retailers and more than 100 large-scale manufacturing units across the country, bis deputy director general Bhupinder Singh said. A market survey conducted in 16 big cities at non-bsi shops revealed that 90 per cent samples failed purity tests with 44.66 per cent declared wide, Singh said.

 New Delhi, Feb. 25: Indias personal computers (pc) market grew by 25 per cent in 2006 with total shipments crossing five million units during the period. In the overall client pc (notebooks and desktops) market, Hewlett Packard retained the top spot with a share of 21 per cent in terms of units shipped, followed by hcl at 14 per cent and Lenovo at 9 per cent.

 New Delhi, Feb. 25: India Incs overseas buying spree, which includes the Tatas takeover of Corus and Hindalcos acquisition of Novelis, could affect the credit profile of corporate sector this year, rating agency Icra has said. 

 Mumbai, Feb. 25: Godrej Consumers Products Ltd (gcpl) is planning to acquire companies in West Asia, Egypt and Africa to expand its hair colour business and hopes to finalise a deal in this calendar year

 New Delhi, Feb. 25: Italian automotive firm Corghi is understood to be in talks with Reliance Retail, which plans to offer vehicle maintenance services to customers.




